### Key Design: Full Round-Trip
# The gRPC transport is invisible to the user. They pass Python dicts in and get Python dicts back.
# Under the hood:
#   1. User calls index_document(index="x", body={"title": "Hello"}, id="1")
#   2. simpledoc_gRPC converts the dict to a protobuf BulkRequest message
#   3. The protobuf is serialized to binary and sent over gRPC (port 9400)
#   4. OpenSearch processes the operation and returns a protobuf BulkResponse
#   5. simpledoc_gRPC converts the response protobuf back to a Python dict
#   6. User receives: {"_index": "x", "_id": "1", "result": "created", ...}

### Wire Size Comparison (per document)
# JSON (REST):     ~220 bytes per document
# Protobuf (gRPC): ~215 bytes per document (~1.4% smaller)
# Note: Document body is still JSON bytes inside protobuf. The savings come from
#       binary-encoded metadata (index, id, routing). Real gRPC advantage is:
#       no HTTP overhead, persistent connections, binary framing, streaming support.
